North Indian Sweets

Jumbo Gulab Jamun: Fried milk balls soaked in sweet syrup, often rose-flavored.

Jinx Jalebi: Deep-fried spirals soaked in sugar syrup.

Jumbo Rasgulla: Soft, spongy balls made from chhena (Indian cottage cheese) soaked in sugar syrup.

King Kaju Katli: Diamond-shaped cashew fudge.

Little Master Ladoo: Round sweets made from flour, ghee, and sugar.

South Indian Sweets
Mysore Pak: A rich, dense sweet made from gram flour, sugar, and ghee.

Payasam: A creamy rice pudding made with milk, sugar, and cardamom.

Unniappam: Small, round fritters made from rice, jaggery, and coconut.

Thala Sweet Pongal: A rice dish cooked with jaggery, ghee, and nuts.

Chinna Thala Coconut Burfi: A fudge-like sweet made from coconut and condensed milk.

East Indian Sweets
Shaana Sandesh: A Bengali sweet made from chhena and sugar.

Jumbo Rasgulla: Also popular in East India, especially in Odisha and West Bengal.

Chhena Poda: A baked sweet made from chhena, sugar, and semolina.

Pitha: Various types of rice cakes, often filled with coconut or jaggery.

Cham Cham: Cylindrical sweets made from chhena, often stuffed with cream.

West Indian Sweets
Gabbar Shrikhand: A creamy dessert made from strained yogurt, sugar, and saffron.

Modak: Sweet dumplings made from rice flour and filled with coconut and jaggery.

Basundi: A thickened milk dessert flavored with cardamom and saffron.

Puran Poli: A sweet flatbread stuffed with a mixture of jaggery and lentils.

Aamras: Mango pulp served with ghee and sometimes milk.
